INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (416001, 'We are betrayed by what is false within.', 18119, 0), (416002, 'If I trim myself to suit others I will soon whittle myself away.', 33, 0), (416003, 'This above all: to thine own self be true.', 13, 0), (416004, 'In the world to come they will not ask me  "Why were you not Moses?" They will ask me  "Why were you not Zusya?"', 65507, 0), (416005, 'A man must be obedient to the promptings of his innermost heart.', 2472, 0), (416006, 'All life is the struggle  the effort to be itself.', 2800, 0), (416007, 'What''s a man''s first duty? The answer is brief: To be himself.', 845, 0), (416008, 'Any path is only a path  and there is no affront  to oneself or to others  in dropping it if that is what your heart tells you.', 1723, 0), (416009, 'It is possible to be different and still be all right.', 21306, 0), (416010, 'Let me listen to me and not to them.', 1267, 0), (416011, 'She lacks confidence  she craves admiration insatiably. She lives on the reflections of herself in the eyes of others. She does not dare to be herself.', 23, 0), (416012, 'I will not cut my conscience to fit this year''s fashions.', 1991, 0), (416013, 'The crow that mimics a cormorant gets drowned.', 18020, 0), (416014, 'Let the world know you as you are  not as you think you should be  because sooner or later  if you are posing  you will forget the pose  and then where are you?', 18086, 0), (416015, 'I was raised to sense what someone wanted me to be and be that kind of person. It took me a long time not to judge myself through someone else''s eyes.', 65508, 0), (416016, 'Education should be the process of helping everyone to discover his uniqueness.', 406, 0), (416017, 'Philosophy is a purely personal matter. A genuine philosopher''s credo is the outcome of a single complex personality  it cannot be transferred. No two persons  if sincere  can have the same philosophy.', 62533, 0), (416018, 'Remember always that you have not only the right to be an individual  you have an obligation to be one.', 141, 0), (416019, 'It is the chiefest point of happiness that a man is willing to be what he is.', 1966, 0), (416020, 'Follow what you love! Don''t deign to ask what "they" are looking for out there. Ask what you have inside. Follow not your interests  which change  but what you are and what you love  which will and should not change.', 65509, 0), (416021, 'All the discontented people I know are trying to be something they are not  to do something they cannot do.', 65510, 0), (416022, 'Dress to please yourself.... Forget you are what you wear.... Wear what you are.', 65511, 0), (416023, 'Resolve to be thyself ... he who finds himself loses his misery!', 460, 0), (416024, 'If we do not rise to the challenge of our unique capacity to shape our lives  to seek the kinds of growth that we find individually fulfilling  then we can have no security: we will live in a world of sham  in which our selves are determined by the will of others  in which we will be constantly buffeted and increasingly isolated by the changes round us.', 65512, 0), (416025, 'Happiness  that grand mistress of the ceremonies in the dance of life  impels us through all its mazes and meanderings  but leads none of us by the same route.', 432, 0), (416026, 'A happy life is one which is in accordance with its own nature.', 62237, 0), (416027, 'Different men seek after happiness in different ways and by different means  and so make for themselves different modes of life.', 1116, 0), (416028, 'All men have happiness as their object: there is no exception. However different the means they employ  they aim at the same end.', 144, 0), (416029, 'Be not imitator  freshly act thy part  Through this world be thou an independent ranger  Better is the faith that springeth from thy heart Than a better faith belonging to a stranger.', 36717, 0), (416030, 'There is always a certain peace in being what one is  in being that completely.', 61075, 0), (416031, 'Posterity weaves no garlands for imitators.', 62240, 0), (416032, '''Tis a gift to be simple  ''tis a gift to be free. ''Tis a gift to come round to where we ought to be. And when we find a place that feels just right  We will be in the valley of love and delight.', 33, 0), (416033, 'You have to deal with the fact that your life is your life.', 21248, 0), (416034, 'I is who I is.', 65513, 0), (416035, 'There are as many ways to live and grow as there are people. Our own ways are the only ways that should matter to us.', 65498, 0), (416036, 'The white light streams down to be broken up by those human prisms into all the colors of the rainbow. Take your own color in the pattern and be just that.', 65514, 0), (416037, 'The search for a new personality is futile  what is fruitful is the human interest the old personality can take in new activities.', 1078, 0), (416038, 'We would have to settle for the elegant goal of becoming ourselves.', 7686, 0), (416039, 'Our concern must be to live while we''re alive ... to release our inner selves from the spiritual death that comes with living behind a facade designed to conform to external definitions of who and what we are.', 1080, 0), (416040, 'I searched through rebellion  drugs  diets  mysticism  religions  intellectu-alism and much more  only to begin to find ... that truth is basically simple-and feels good  clean and right.', 65515, 0), (416041, 'If you''re gonna be a failure  at least be one at something you enjoy.', 35699, 0), (416042, 'That suit is best that best suits me.', 65516, 0), (416043, 'The self is not something that one finds. It is something one creates.', 1678, 0), (416044, 'Your readiest desire is your path to joy ... even if it destroys you.', 13875, 0), (416045, 'Individuals learn faster than institutions and it is always the dinosaur''s brain that is the last to get the new messages.', 62245, 0), (416046, 'Go ahead and do it. It''s much easier to apologize after something''s been done than to get permission ahead of time.', 19501, 0), (416047, 'Innovators are inevitably controversial.', 54696, 0), (416048, 'I''m not going to limit myself just because some people won''t accept the fact that I can do something else.', 1300, 0), (416049, 'Criticism ... makes very little dent upon me  unless I think there is some real justification and something should be done.', 141, 0), (416050, 'It is healthier  in any case  to write for the adults one''s children will become than for the children one''s "mature" critics often are.', 753, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (416051, 'I was the kind nobody thought could make it. I had a funny Boston accent. I couldn''t pronounce my R''s. I wasn''t a beauty.', 64122, 0), (416052, 'Power is strength and the ability to see yourself through your own eyes and not through the eyes of another.', 65517, 0), (416053, 'Getting fit is a political act-you are taking charge of your life.', 64250, 0), (416054, 'I''m uncomfortable when I''m comfortable ... I can''t help it  it''s my personality.', 65518, 0), (416055, 'For a long time the only time I felt beautiful-in the sense of being complete as a woman  as a human being  and even female-was when I was singing.', 62943, 0), (416056, 'The source of continuing aliveness was to find your passion and pursue it  with whole heart and single mind.', 30206, 0), (416057, 'I look at ordinary people in their suits  them with no scars  and I''m different. I don''t fit with them. I''m where everybody''s got scar tissue on their eyes and got noses like saddles. I go to conventions of old fighters like me and I see the scar tissue and all them flat noses and it''s beautiful. ... They talk like me  like they got rocks in their throats. Beautiful!', 65519, 0), (416058, 'I have the feeling when I write poetry that I''m doing what I''m supposed to do. You don''t think about whether you''re going to get money or fame  you just do it.', 65520, 0), (416059, 'A door that seems to stand open must be of a man''s size  or it is not the door that providence means for him.', 2175, 0), (416060, 'I have the true feeling of myself only when I am unbearably unhappy.', 629, 0), (416061, 'Mountains should be climbed with as little effort as possible and without desire. The reality of your own nature should determine the speed. If you become restless  speed up. If you become winded  slow down. You climb the mountain in an equilibrium between restlessness and exhaustion. Then  when you''re no longer thinking ahead  each footstep isn''t just a means to an end  but a unique event in itself.', 1742, 0), (416062, 'It is the soul''s duty to be loyal to its own desires.', 7216, 0), (416063, 'In the first grade  I already knew the pattern of my life. I didn''t know the living of it  but I knew the line. ... From the first day in school until the day I graduated  everyone gave me one hundred plus in art. Well  where do you go in life? You go to the place where you got one hundred plus.', 51621, 0), (416064, 'I am a writer because writing is the thing I do best.', 931, 0), (416065, 'Each of us has some unique capability waiting for realization. Every person is valuable in his own existence  for himself alone ... each of us can bring to fruition these innate  God-given abilities.', 65521, 0), (416066, 'All of us attain the greatest success and happiness possible in this life whenever we use our native capacities to their fullest extent. ... And every life must be chalked up at least a partial failure when it does not succeed in reaching its inherent destiny.', 54020, 0), (416067, 'The same man cannot be skilled in everything  each has his special excellence.', 542, 0), (416068, 'Any talent that we are born with eventually surfaces as a need.', 65522, 0), (416069, 'The best career advice given to the young ... is "Find out what you like doing best and get someone to pay you for doing it."', 62901, 0), (416070, 'Skills vary with the man. We must... strive by that which is born in us.', 16113, 0), (416071, 'People are always neglecting something they can do in trying to do something they can''t do.', 20175, 0), (416072, 'A man like Verdi must write like Verdi.', 65523, 0), (416073, 'I write lustily and humorously. It isn''t calculated  it''s the way I think. I''ve invented a writing style that expresses who I am.', 405, 0), (416074, 'Each citizen should play his part in the community according to his individual gifts.', 51, 0), (416075, 'Genius does what it must  talent does what it can.', 5223, 0), (416076, 'Everything keeps its best nature only by being put to its best use.', 22130, 0), (416077, 'We don''t see many fat men walking on stilts.', 65524, 0), (416078, 'I was playing it like Willie Wilson  but I forgot that I''m in Clint Hurdle''s body.', 65525, 0), (416079, 'We succeed in enterprises which demand the positive qualities we possess  but we excel in those which can also make use of our defects.', 4021, 0), (416080, 'I wrote because I had to. I couldn''t stop. There wasn''t anything else I could do. If no one ever bought anything  anything I ever did  I''d still be writing. It''s beyond a compulsion.', 355, 0), (416081, 'To every man according to his ability.', 5587, 0), (416082, 'If a man is called to be a streetsweep-er  he should sweep streets even as Michelangelo painted  or Beethoven composed music  or Shakespeare wrote poetry. He should sweep streets so well that all the hosts of heaven and earth will pause to say  here lived a great streetsweeper who did his job well.', 21767, 0), (416083, 'Men whose trade is rat-catching  love to catch rats  the bug destroyer seizes on his bug with delight  and the suppressor is gratified by finding his vice.', 9771, 0), (416084, 'Brutes find out where their talents lie  a bear will not attempt to fly.', 995, 0), (416085, 'We may fail of our happiness  strive we ever so bravely  but we are less likely to fail if we measure with judgment our chances and our capabilities.', 24996, 0), (416086, 'The greatest achievement of the human spirit is to live up to one''s opportunities and make the most of one''s resources.', 62195, 0), (416087, 'The test of a vocation is the love of the drudgery it involves.', 1014, 0), (416088, 'Are you doing the kind of work you were built for  so that you can expect to be able to do very large amounts of that kind and thrive under it? Or are you doing a kind of which you can do comparatively little?', 14130, 0), (416089, 'Starting out to make money is the greatest mistake in life. Do what you feel you have a flair for doing  and if you are good enough at it  the money will come.', 65526, 0), (416090, 'Whenever it is possible  a boy should choose some occupation which he should do even if he did not need the money.', 6067, 0), (416091, 'The fun of being alive is realizing you have a talent and you can use it every day so it grows stronger.... And if you''re in an atmosphere where this talent is appreciated instead of just tolerated  why  it''s just as good as sex.', 65527, 0), (416092, 'It is only when I am doing my work that I feel truly alive. It is like having sex.', 19735, 0), (416093, 'If a man has a talent and cannot use it  he has failed. If he has a talent and uses only half of it  he has partly failed. If he has a talent and learns somehow to use the whole of it  he has gloriously succeeded  and won a satisfaction and a triumph few men ever know.', 1971, 0), (416094, 'The high prize of life  the crowning fortune of a man  is to be born with a bias to some pursuit which finds him in employment and happiness.', 760, 0), (416095, 'Everybody undertakes what he sees another successful in  whether he has the aptitude for it or not.', 62224, 0), (416096, 'To find out what one is fitted to do  and to secure an opportunity to do it  is the key to happiness.', 2575, 0), (416097, 'The road to happiness lies in two simple principles: find what interests you and that you can do well  and put your whole soul into it-every bit of energy and ambition and natural ability you have.', 64191, 0), (416098, 'One should stick to the sort of thing for which one was made  I tried to be an herbalist  whereas I should keep to the butcher''s trade.', 2843, 0), (416099, 'If you have to support yourself  you had bloody well better find some way that is going to be interesting.', 205, 0), (416100, 'When men are rightfully occupied  then their amusement grows out of their work as the color petals out of a fruitful garden.', 485, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (416101, 'A musician must make music  an artist must paint  a poet must write  if he to be at peace with himself. What a man can be  he must be.', 62519, 0), (416102, 'We do not write as we want but as we can.', 235, 0), (416103, 'Never desert your own line of talent. Be what nature intended you for  and you will succeed.', 9771, 0), (416104, 'Nature arms each man with some faculty which enables him to do easily some feat impossible to any other.', 760, 0), (416105, 'It is not a dreamlike state  but the somehow insulated state  that a great musician achieves in a great performance. He''s aware of where he is and what he''s doing  but his mind is on the playing of his instrument with an internal sense of Tightness-it is not merely mechanical  it is not only spiritual  it is something of both  on a different plane and a more remote one.', 24450, 0), (416106, 'We will discover the nature of our particular genius when we stop trying to conform to our own or to other people''s models  learn to be ourselves  and allow our natural channel to open.', 39554, 0), (416107, 'It requires a certain kind of mind to see beauty in a hamburger bun. Yet  is it any more unusual to find grace in the texture and softly curved silhouette of a bun than to reflect lovingly on ... the arrangement of textures and colors in a butterfly''s wing?', 37739, 0), (416108, 'The question "Who ought to be boss" is like asking "Who ought to be tenor in the quartet?" Obviously  the man who can sing tenor.', 1796, 0), (416109, 'I''m a salami writer. I try to write good salami  but salami is salami.', 578, 0), (416110, 'I''d rather be a failure at something I enjoy than a success at something I hate.', 1643, 0), (416111, 'I cannot do everything  but still I can do something  and because I cannot do everything  I will not refuse to do the something that I can do.', 31769, 0), (416112, 'What really matters is what you do with what you have.', 65528, 0), (416113, 'I know that I haven''t powers enough to divide myself into one who earns and one who creates.', 44106, 0), (416114, 'Man is not born to solve the problems of the universe  but to find out what he has to do ... within the limits of his comprehension.', 62224, 0), (416115, 'The weakest among us has a gift  however seemingly trivial  which is peculiar to him and which worthily used will be a gift also to his race.', 485, 0), (416116, 'Every person is responsible for all the good within the scope of his abilities  and for no more.', 65529, 0), (416117, 'Me  I''m just a hack. I''m just a schlep-per. I just do what I can do.', 1688, 0), (416118, 'The great law of culture: Let each become all that he was created capable of being.', 3061, 0), (416119, 'Don''t bother just to be better than your contemporaries or predecessors. Try to be better than yourself.', 344, 0), (416120, 'God requires a faithful fulfillment of the merest trifle given us to do  rather than the most ardent aspiration to things to which we are not called.', 63291, 0), (416121, 'When I was young  I said to God  "God  tell me the mystery of the universe." But God answered  "That knowledge is reserved for me alone." So I said  "God  tell me the mystery of the peanut." Then God said  "Well George  that''s more nearly your size." And he told me.', 14728, 0), (416122, 'I long to accomplish a great and noble task  but it is my chief duty to accomplish small tasks as if they were great and noble.', 701, 0), (416123, 'We may fail of our happiness  strive we ever so bravely  but we are less likely to fail if we measure with judgment our chances and our capabilities.', 24996, 0), (416124, 'No amount of study or learning will make a man a leader unless he has the natural qualities of one.', 65530, 0), (416125, 'Choose a subject equal to your abilities  think carefully what your shoulders may refuse  and what they are capable of bearing.', 2542, 0), (416126, 'In efforts to soar above our nature  we invariably fall below it.', 49, 0), (416127, 'The driver knows how much the ox can carry  and keeps the ox from being overloaded. You know your way and your state of mind. Do not carry too much.', 62701, 0), (416128, 'If you could once make up your mind never to undertake more work ... than you can carry on calmly  quietly  without hurry or flurry ... and if the instant you feel yourself growing nervous and ... out of breath  you would stop and take breath  you would find this simple common-sense rule doing for you what no prayers or tears could ever accomplish.', 24226, 0), (416129, 'The deepest personal defeat suffered by human beings is constituted by the difference between what one was capable of becoming  and what one has in fact become.', 28831, 0), (416130, 'What I wanted was to be allowed to do the thing in the world that I did best-which I believed then and believe now is the greatest privilege there is. When I did that  success found me.', 54990, 0), (416131, 'I had already learned from more than a decade of political life that I was going to be criticized no matter what I did  so I might as well be criticized for something I wanted to do.', 19480, 0), (416132, 'There is only one success-to be able to spend your life in your own way.', 8661, 0), (416133, 'The only success worth one''s powder was success in the line of one''s idiosyncrasy ... what was talent but the art of being completely whatever one happened to be?', 561, 0), (416134, 'We are traditionally rather proud of ourselves for having slipped creative work in there between the domestic chores and obligations. I''m not sure we deserve such big A-pluses for all that.', 171, 0), (416135, 'Success based on anything but internal fulfillment is bound to be empty.', 65531, 0), (416136, 'We succeed in enterprises which demand the positive qualities we possess  but we excel in those which can also make use of our defects.', 4021, 0), (416137, 'All I would tell people is to hold on to what was individual about themselves  not to allow their ambition for success to cause them to try to imitate the success of others. You''ve got to find in on your own terms.', 12392, 0), (416138, 'For me  writing is the only thing that passes the three tests of metier: (i) when I''m doing it  I don''t feel that I should be doing something else instead  (2) it produces a sense of accomplishment and  once in a while  pride  and (3) it''s frightening.', 1739, 0), (416139, 'One can never consent to creep when one feels an impulse to soar.', 701, 0), (416140, 'My mother said to me  "If you become a soldier  you''ll be a general  if you become a monk you''ll end up as the pope." Instead  I became a painter and wound up as Picasso.', 981, 0), (416141, 'We only do well the things we like doing.', 244, 0), (416142, 'Abasement  degradation is simply the manner of life of the man who has refused to be what it is his duty to be.', 2800, 0), (416143, 'Different people have different duties assigned to them by Nature  Nature has given one the power or the desire to do this  the other that. Each bird must sing with his own throat.', 33, 0), (416144, 'A first rate soup is better than a second rate painting.', 62519, 0), (416145, 'We can''t all be heroes  because someone has to sit on the curb and clap as they go by.', 1122, 0), (416146, 'Nature magically suits a man to his fortunes  by making them the fruit of his character.', 760, 0), (416147, 'I''d rather be a lamppost in Chicago than a millionaire in any other city.', 65532, 0), (416148, 'Whatever you are by nature  keep to it  never desert your own line of talent. Be what nature intended you for  and you will succeed  be anything else and you will be ten thousand times worse than nothing.', 9771, 0), (416149, 'Ask yourself the secret of your success. Listen to your answer  and practice it.', 424, 0), (416150, 'Do what you love  the money will follow.', 65522, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (416151, 'I am only one  but still I am one. I cannot do everything  but still I can do something  and because I cannot do everything  I will not refuse to do something I can do.', 31769, 0), (416152, 'Starting out to make money is the greatest mistake in life. Do what you feel you have a flair for doing  and if you are good enough at it  the money will come.', 65526, 0), (416153, 'If a man has a talent and cannot use it  he has failed. If he has a talent and uses only half of it  he has partly failed. If he has a talent and learns somehow to use the whole of it  he has gloriously succeeded  and won a satisfaction and a triumph few men ever know.', 1971, 0), (416154, 'A man can do only what he can do. But if he does that each day he can sleep at night and do it again the next day.', 1006, 0), (416155, 'Don''t take anyone else''s definition of success as your own. (This is easier said than done.)', 63279, 0), (416156, 'You must be holy in the way God asks you to be holy. God does not ask you to be a Trappist monk or a hermit. He wills that you sanctify your everyday life.', 65533, 0), (416157, 'Bloom where you are planted.', 33, 0), (416158, 'The first duty of a human being is to assume the right relationship to society-more briefly  to find your real job  and do it.', 63146, 0), (416159, 'The great enemy of clear language is insincerity. When there is a gap between one''s real and one''s declared aims  one turns  as it were  instinctively to long words and exhausted idioms  like a cuttlefish squirting out ink.', 521, 0), (416160, 'We don''t know who we are until we see what we can do.', 2702, 0), (416161, 'If Heaven made him  earth can find some use for him.', 7652, 0), (416162, 'Don''t do anything that someone else can do for you because there are only so many things that only you can do.', 63539, 0), (416163, 'The hole and the patch should be commensurate.', 1207, 0), (416164, 'The things that one most wants to do are the things that are probably most worth doing.', 28298, 0), (416165, 'If all misfortunes were laid in one common heap whence everyone must take an equal portion  most people would be contented to take their own and depart.', 1595, 0), (416166, 'Every true man  sir  who is a little above the level of the beasts and plants  lives so as to give a meaning and a value to his own life.', 23247, 0), (416167, 'Sir  I would rather be right than be President.', 46469, 0), (416168, 'He will hew to the line of right  let the chips fly where they may.', 62302, 0), (416169, 'Be sure you are right  then go ahead.', 17494, 0), (416170, 'Two wrongs can never make a right.', 41936, 0), (416171, 'Let us have faith that Right makes Might  and in that faith let us to the end dare to do our duty as we understand it.', 1012, 0), (416172, 'Right is the eternal sun  the world cannot delay its coming.', 24952, 0), (416173, 'One truth is clear  Whatever is is right.', 3348, 0), (416174, 'Heaven itself has ordained the right.', 3161, 0), (416175, 'Wherever there is a human being  I see God-given rights inherent in that being  whatever may be the sex or complexion.', 55740, 0), (416176, 'The equal right of all men to the use of land is as clear as their equal right to breathe the air - it is a right proclaimed by the fact of their existence. For we cannot suppose that some men have a right to be in this world  and others no right.', 40782, 0), (416177, 'Equal rights for all  special privileges for none.', 1207, 0), (416178, 'You risk just as much in being credulous as in being suspicious.', 2879, 0), (416179, 'Our whole way of life today is dedicated to the removal of risk. Cradle to grave we are supported  insulated  and isolated from the risks of life- and if we fall  our government stands ready with Band-Aids of every size.', 17052, 0), (416180, 'Any life truly lived is a risky business  and if one puts up too many fences against the risks one ends by shutting out life itself.', 