n do-can love things that no one else can love. We are like violins. We can be used for doorstops  or we can make music.', 30125, 0), (417033, 'If God had wanted me otherwise  He would have created me otherwise.', 62224, 0), (417034, 'Love your self''s self where it lives.', 164, 0), (417035, 'I am what I am  so take me as I am!', 62224, 0), (417036, 'Be content with what you are  and wish not change  nor dread your last day  nor long for it.', 62597, 0), (417037, 'It is the chiefest point of happiness that a man is willing to be what he is.', 1966, 0), (417038, 'Who I am is the best I can be.', 62943, 0), (417039, 'Oh  I''m so inadequate. And I love myself!', 65627, 0), (417040, 'Learn what you are and be such.', 16113, 0), (417041, 'What thou art  that thou art.', 946, 0), (417042, 'I is who I is.', 65513, 0), (417043, 'People remain what they are  even when their faces fall to pieces.', 1140, 0), (417044, 'You have to deal with the fact that your life is your life.', 21248, 0), (417045, 'The search for a new personality is futile  what is fruitful is the interest the old personality can take in new activities.', 1078, 0), (417046, 'I seldom think about my limitations  and they never make me sad. Perhaps there is just a touch of yearning at times  but it is vague  like a breeze among flowers.', 701, 0), (417047, 'In order to be irreplaceable one must always be different.', 111, 0), (417048, 'The courage to be is the courage to accept oneself  in spite of being unacceptable.', 2750, 0), (417049, 'Contentment  and indeed usefulness  comes as the infallible result of great acceptances  great humilities-of not trying to conform to some dramatized version of ourselves.', 10420, 0), (417050, 'A man should not strive to eliminate his complexes but to get into accord with them  for they are legitimately what directs his conduct in the world.', 555, 0);
