ree  six  ten or twenty years old. More noticeably so  perhaps  at six or seven  because we were not pretending so much then.', 94, 0), (417448, 'Until we see what we are  we cannot take steps to become what we should be.', 63146, 0), (417449, 'When a man begins to understand himself  he begins to live.', 65680, 0), (417450, 'A humble knowledge of oneself is a surer road to God than a deep searching of the sciences.', 946, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (417451, 'If you do not ask yourself what it is you know  you will go on listening to others and change will not come because you will not hear your own truth.', 64455, 0), (417452, 'No man remains quite what he was when he recognizes himself.', 778, 0), (417453, 'Sometimes a person has to go back  really back-to have a sense  an understanding of all that''s gone to make them-before they can go forward.', 33810, 0), (417454, 'Awakening begins when a man realizes that he is going nowhere and does not know where to go.', 63057, 0), (417455, 'Self-searching is the means by which we bring new vision  action  and grace to bear upon the dark and negative side of our natures. With it comes the development of that kind of humility that makes it possible for us to receive God''s help. ... We find that bit by bit we can discard the old life-the one that did not work-for a new life that can and does work under conditions whatever.', 33, 0), (417456, 'The most difficult thing in life is to know yourself.', 64386, 0), (417457, 'You never find yourself until you face the truth.', 27040, 0), (417458, 'It is not only the most difficult thing to know oneself  but the most inconvenient  too.', 3355, 0), (417459, 'Long ago I understood that it wasn''t merely my being a woman that was preventing my being welcomed into the world of what I long thought of as my peers. It was that I had succeeded in an undertaking few men have even attempted: I have become myself.', 24969, 0), (417460, 'He knows the universe and does not know himself.', 2843, 0), (417461, 'There are chapters in every life which are seldom read and certainly not aloud.', 6042, 0), (417462, 'No man ever understands quite his own artful dodges to escape from the grim shadow of self-knowledge.', 1241, 0), (417463, 'Nothing is easier than self-deceit.', 3291, 0), (417464, 'Sometimes it takes years to really grasp what has happened to your life.', 60458, 0), (417465, 'One may understand the cosmos  but never the ego  the self is more distant than any star.', 263, 0), (417466, 'You can live a lifetime and  at the end of it  know more about other people than you know about yourself.', 8218, 0), (417467, 'Learn what you are  and be such.', 16113, 0), (417468, 'Long tresses down to the floor can be beautiful  if you have that  but learn to love what you have.', 12437, 0), (417469, 'I am no longer what I was. I will remain what I have become.', 111, 0), (417470, 'I always introduce myself as an encyclopedia of defects which I do not deny. Why should I? It took me a whole life to build myself as I am.', 10057, 0), (417471, 'The happy man is he who knows his limitations  yet bows to no false gods.', 1323, 0), (417472, 'I shall be an autocrat  that''s my trade  and the good Lord will forgive me  that''s his.', 33381, 0), (417473, 'Sometimes it is more important to discover what one cannot do  than what one can.', 1317, 0), (417474, 'Somehow we learn who we really are and then live with that decision.', 141, 0), (417475, 'Self-understanding rather than self-condemnation is the way to inner peace and mature conscience.', 62208, 0), (417476, 'To say something nice about themselves  this is the hardest thing in the world for people to do.', 28584, 0), (417477, 'After my screen test  the director clapped his hands gleefully and yelled  "She can''t talk! She can''t act! She''s sensational!"', 4264, 0), (417478, 'Whenever I dwell for any length of time on my own shortcomings  they gradually begin to seem mild  harmless  rather engaging little things  not at all like the staring defects in other people''s characters.', 63027, 0), (417479, 'It''s not our disadvantages or shortcomings that are ridiculous  but rather the studious way we try to hide them  and our desire to act as if they did not exist.', 7895, 0), (417480, 'Of all the idiots I have met in my life  and the Lord knows that they have not been few or little  I think that I have been the biggest.', 19178, 0), (417481, 'A woman of mystique is fully aware of her flaws and weaknesses  yet she is strong enough to admit them and not be embarrassed by them.', 65681, 0), (417482, 'Learning too soon our limitations  we never learn our powers.', 1932, 0), (417483, 'Your thorns are the best part of you.', 8786, 0), (417484, 'Oh  I''m so inadequate. And I love myself!', 65627, 0), (417485, 'I am simple  complex  generous  selfish  unattractive  beautiful  lazy  and driven.', 3756, 0), (417486, 'If your head tells you one thing and your heart tells you another  before you do anything  you should first decide whether you have a better head or a better heart.', 814, 0), (417487, 'I did not lose myself all at once. I rubbed out my face over the years washing away my pain  the same way carvings on stone are worn down by water.', 1039, 0), (417488, 'The precept  "Know yourself " was not solely intended to obviate the pride of mankind  but likewise that we might understand our own worth.', 20928, 0), (417489, 'I believe that dreams transport us through the underside of our days  and that if we wish to become acquainted with the dark side of what we are  the signposts are there  waiting for us to translate them.', 15819, 0), (417490, 'It is a purely relative matter where one draws the plimsoll-line of condemnation  and ... if you find the whole of humanity falls below it you have simply made a mistake and drawn it too high. And you are probably below it yourself.', 43099, 0), (417491, 'I''m a salami writer. I try to write good salami  but salami is salami.', 578, 0), (417492, 'Only by pursuing the extremes in one''s nature  with all its contradictions  appetites  aversions  rages  can one hope to understand a little ... oh  I admit only a very little ... of what life is about.', 642, 0), (417493, 'The basic experience of everyone is the experience of human limitation.', 931, 0), (417494, 'We do not make beams from the hollow  decaying trunk of the fallen oak. We use the upsoaring tree in the full vigor of its sap.', 65682, 0), (417495, 'We must use what we have to invent what we desire.', 809, 0), (417496, 'Whatever glory belongs to the race for a development unprecedented in history for the given length of time  a full share belongs to the womanhood of the race.', 25698, 0), (417497, 'There is a potential heroine in every woman.', 10238, 0), (417498, 'We are volcanoes. When we women offer our experience as our truth  as human truth  all the maps change. There are new mountains.', 62247, 0), (417499, 'I hear the singing of the lives of women. The clear mystery  the offering  the pride.', 1736, 0), (417500, 'The sexes in each species of beings . . . are always true equivalents-equals but not identicals.', 63990, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (417501, 'For women there are  undoubtedly  great difficulties in the path  but so much the more to overcome. First no woman would say "I am but a woman!" But a woman! What more can you ask to be?', 6136, 0), (417502, 'Ability is sexless.', 65683, 0), (417503, 'We bear the world and we make it.... There was never a great man who had not a great mother-it is hardly an exaggeration.', 25143, 0), (417504, 'Remember  Ginger Rogers did everything Fred Astaire did  but she did it backwards and in high heels.', 65684, 0), (417505, 'There may be ways in which we can work for change. We don''t have to do dramatic things or devote our entire lives to it. We can lead normal lives but at the same time try hard not to be bystanders.', 65685, 0), (417506, 'Some people give time  some money  some their skills and connections  some literally give their life''s blood . . . but everyone has something to give.', 11962, 0), (417507, 'Though I have no productive worth  I have a certain value as an indestructible quantity.', 3447, 0), (417508, 'I was once the typical daughter  then the easily recognizable wife  and then the quintessential mother. I seem always to have reminded people of someone in their family. Perhaps I am just the triumph of Plain Jane.', 4743, 0), (417509, 'God wastes nothing.', 13871, 0), (417510, 'To be a housewife is ... a difficult  a wrenching  sometimes ungrateful job if it''s looked on as only a job. Regarded as a profession  it is the noblest as it is the most ancient of the catalogue. Let none persuade us differently  or the world will be lost indeed.', 4867, 0), (417511, 'It''s this no-nonsense side of women that is pleasant to deal with. They are the real sportsmen.', 4867, 0), (417512, 'Not being beautiful was the true blessing. ... Not being beautiful forced me to develop my inner resources. The pretty girl has a handicap to overcome.', 12971, 0), (417513, 'There is not one big cosmic meaning for a